\begin_layout Standard
Although halo biases are constant on large scales, halo biases on small
 scales are scale-dependent (XXX:reference).
 We explore whether the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples have different scale-dependence in small scale halo biases.
 In order to explore that, we take the ratio of the cross correlation functions
 between the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples and normalize it with their linear biases.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

 shows the ratios for several mass bins.
 The first three mass bins labeled in the figure, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}M[h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}]=11.7,12.0,12.2}$
\end_inset

, are from the Bolshoi simulation, and the last two mass bins, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}M[h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}]=12.7,13.1}$
\end_inset

, are from the MultiDark simulation.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples have very different scale-dependence, especially around 1 to
 2
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the difference on small scales becomes larger for lower halo
 mass samples.

\color red
 Those low mass halos in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples are likely to be close to massive halos 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to now, we use both host halos and ejected halos to compute halo biases.
 Both types of halos are identified as distinct halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Ejected halos, however, are halos which were identified as a part of a
 more massive halos at one or more occasions in the past.
 Those ejected halos tend to exist around a more massive halos (any reference?),
 and only some of them may be gravitationally bound to other more massive
 halos.
 Therefore, the efect on the scale-dependent biases may be caused by those
 ejected halos.
 To test this, we compute halo-matter cross correlation functions without
 the ejected halos.
 Similar to Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

, we first compare linear biases as a function of halo mass.
 We observe that the ratios of linear biases between the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples are suppressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10\%$
\end_inset

.
 Next, we compare cross correlation functions on small scales, as shown
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:eject"

\end_inset

, similar to what was done in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:eject"

\end_inset

 only shows the results for low mass halos from 
\color red
the Bolshoi simulation.
 This is because
\color inherit
 we do not find many ejected halos in the MultiDark simulation due to its
 mass resolution.
 
\color black
Once the ejected halos have been removed, the deviation of the halo bias
 on small scales is greatly reduced.
 
\color inherit
This implies an intimate connection between assembly bias and subhalo back-splas
hing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that halos which have different 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 cluster differently even when those halos have the same virial mass.
 In particular, the scale-dependence of halo biases on small scales is significa
ntly different, which is mainly caused by the ejected halos.
 
\end_layout

